    "content": "<html>\n<head>\n    <title>NP-Completeness</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <h1>NP-Completeness Example</h1>\n    <p>NP-Completeness is a concept in computer science that refers to a problem that is undecidable, meaning it cannot be solved exactly for all possible inputs.</p>\n    <p>A simple example of NP-Completeness is the \"Halting Problem\". The Halting Problem states that given a program and its input, can the program ever run forever or stop? In other words, can a program ever be \"deadlocked\"?</p>\n    <script>\n        function haltingProblem(program, input) {\n            // Simulate the program running\n            let output = program(input);\n            // If the output is always 0, the program will run forever\n            if (output === 0) {\n                return true;\n            }\n            // If the output is always 1, the program will run forever\n            else if (output === 1) {\n                return true;\n            }\n            // If the output is neither 0 nor 1, the program will not run forever\n            else {\n                return false;\n            }\n        }\n\n        // Example usage:\n        let program = (input) => {\n            // This is a very simple program that always outputs 0\n            return 0;\n        };\n\n        let input = \"Hello, World!\";\n        console.log(haltingProblem(program, input));\n    </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
